sup id=\"cite_ref-7\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Rodney_Robert_Porter#cite_note-7\"><span>[<\/span>7<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-8\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Rodney_Robert_Porter#cite_note-8\"><span>[<\/span>8<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-9\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Rodney_Robert_Porter#cite_note-9\"><span>[<\/span>9<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-10\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Rodney_Robert_Porter#cite_note-10\"><span>[<\/span>10<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-11\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Rodney_Robert_Porter#cite_note-11\"><span>[<\/span>11<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup><\/p><p>Born in <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Newton-le-Willows\" title=\"Newton-le-Willows\">Newton-le-Willows<\/a>, <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Metropolitan_Borough_of_St_Helens\" title=\"Metropolitan Borough of St Helens\">St Helens<\/a>, Lancashire, England, Rodney Robert Porter received his Bachelors of Sciences degree from the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/University_of_Liverpool\" title=\"University of Liverpool\">University of Liverpool<\/a> in 1939 for <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Biochemistry\" title=\"Biochemistry\">Biochemistry<\/a>. He moved to the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/University_of_Cambridge\" title=\"University of Cambridge\">University of Cambridge<\/a> where he became <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Fred_Sanger\" title=\"Fred Sanger\" class=\"mw-redirect\">Fred Sanger<\/a>'s first PhD student. He was awarded his doctorate in 1948.<\/p><p>He worked for the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/National_Institute_for_Medical_Research\" title=\"National Institute for Medical Research\">National Institute for Medical Research<\/a> for eleven years (1949\u20131960) before joining <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/St_Mary%27s_Hospital_(London)\" title=\"St Mary's Hospital (London)\" class=\"mw-redirect\">St. Mary's Hospital Medical School<\/a>, <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Imperial_College_London\" title=\"Imperial College London\">Imperial College London<\/a> and becoming the Pfizer Professor of Immunology. In 1967 he was appointed Whitley Professor of Biochemistry at the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/University_of_Oxford\" title=\"University of Oxford\">University of Oxford<\/a>, and Fellow of <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Trinity_College,_Oxford\" title=\"Trinity College, Oxford\">Trinity College<\/a>. His colleague <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Elizabeth_Press\" title=\"Elizabeth Press\">Elizabeth Press<\/a> (Betty Press) worked with him at NIMR, St Mary's and at Oxford contributing extensively to the work which led to the Nobel Prize.<\/p><p>In 1972, Porter shared the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Nobel_Prize_for_Medicine\" title=\"Nobel Prize for Medicine\" class=\"mw-redirect\">Nobel Prize for Medicine<\/a> or Physiology with <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Gerald_M._Edelman\" title=\"Gerald M. Edelman\" class=\"mw-redirect\">Gerald M. Edelman<\/a> for determining the chemical structure of an <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Antibody\" title=\"Antibody\">antibody<\/a>. Using the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Enzyme\" title=\"Enzyme\">enzyme<\/a> <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Papain\" title=\"Papain\">papain<\/a>, he broke the blood's <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Immunoglobin\" title=\"Immunoglobin\" class=\"mw-redirect\">immunoglobin<\/a> into fragments, making them easier to study. He also looked into how the blood's immunoglobins react with cellular surfaces. He subsequently worked with colleagues Kenneth BM Reid, Robert Sim and Duncan Campbell on developing understanding of the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Complementarity_(molecular_biology)\" title=\"Complementarity (molecular biology)\">Complement<\/a> Proteins associated with defence against infection.<\/p><p>In 1991, <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Raymond_Dwek\" title=\"Raymond Dwek\">Raymond Dwek<\/a> founded the Oxford Glycobiology Institute at the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Department_of_Biochemistry,_University_of_Oxford\" title=\"Department of Biochemistry, University of Oxford\">Department of Biochemistry, University of Oxford<\/a> and this building was named after Porter as the Rodney Porter building.<\/p><p>He died in a road accident near <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Winchester\" title=\"Winchester\">Winchester<\/a>, Hampshire and is survived by his wife and five children.<\/p>","name":"Rodney Robert Porter","place_of_birth":"Newton-le-Willows , Lancashire","place_of_death":null,"text":"Rodney Robert Porter , Physiology or Medicine, 1972","year":1972.0}